summary: Crowley and Aziraphale having their first real date at the Ritz?
question: Crowley and Aziraphale having their first real date at the Ritz?
answer:
They had both been to the Ritz many different times, but generally with the same reasoning. It was their thing, the Ritz. Nothing about going to the Ritz together was unfamiliar territory, except for the one new detail being brought to the forefront.

This was their first time going to the Ritz on a proper date.

Crowley and Aziraphale had danced around the word “date” for nearly the entirety of the word’s existence, insisting most times that they were only friends out for some fun together. No dates. None.
Until Crowley finally decided it was time Aziraphale knew how he felt and to his surprise Aziraphale admitted to sharing those very same feelings.

Now, they were going on a date.

Crowley was terrified (though to anyone who asked he would insist he was merely a little ruffled over the change) as he smoothed his hands over his suit for the fifteenth time in the past five minutes. No, he most definitely had not been counting the minutes.
That would be silly.
Crowley was not silly, he was very serious and intimidating.

He was standing at Aziraphale’s bookshop door, patiently waiting for the angel who was frantically calling from inside, “I’ll be there in just a moment, dear! I’ve lost my coat!” Crowley was on the brink of suggesting Aziraphale just miracle up a new one and worry about the lost coat later when the door swung open to revealed a flushed, flustered Aziraphale. “Hello, dear.”
“Hey, angel.” Crowley greeted, denying vehemently that he was starstruck by the sight of his love. Aziraphale grinned as though he had an idea of the effect he was having on the demon anyways, a fact further proven when he leaned forward to press a delicate kiss to Crowley’s cheek.
Surely he knew that would make Crowley blush like an idiot.

“Ready to go, then?” Crowley asked instead of saying something stupid, offering his arm with the shyest hint of a smile.
“Ready as ever.” Aziraphale took his arm with his own, smiling merrily the whole time. Such a cute smile it was.

Together, arm in arm, the Angel and the Demon headed towards the Bentley.

tags: karamo gives us all of the confidence
tan and crowleys fashion statements would rule the world
body:
Good Omens Meets Queer Eye

Is it just me or would the Fab Five get along so well with our ineffable husbands?

•Aziraphale and Antoni in the kitchen being the two soft muffins they are swapping recipes and regaling tales of exotic cuisine.

•

•

• Karamo would be the best for Aziraphale’s confidence because let’s be honest…Gabriel’s comment really got to him.

•

•

• Tan and Crowley would be snark-bros and be buried knee-deep in skinny jeans and bond over best friends and their desperate attempts to fix their odd(Johnathan) or outdated (Aziraphale) wardrobes.

•

•

• Bobby, Aziraphale, and Antoni would be chatting in the kitchen like adults while Johnathan, Crowley, Tan, and Karamo (Karamo would go back and forth between the groups) are in the living room being the giant children they are.

•

•

• Crowley and Jonathan. That’s it.

•

•

• Just imagine all the gay.

summary: I'm gonna die on this hill but I 1000% believe that even if Aziraphale and Crowley hadn't changed places they still would've...
body: I’m gonna die on this hill but I 1000% believe that even if Aziraphale and Crowley hadn’t changed places they still would’ve survived. Adam got to choose his nature and, I believe, so did they. There’s this undercurrent of an argument about nature versus nurture with a lot of the characters. It all comes down to choices. Their relationship and their subsequent choice to work against armageddon shows that they can go against their “innate” nature, they can choose. “All of Us against all of Them”. They chose not to be angel or demon, they chose humanity. And that’s why I think it wouldn’t have mattered if they didn’t change places, they’re fundamentally different now.
